# BabelNet  

BabelNet is a [multilingual](/Multilinguality) lexical‑semantic [knowledge graph](/Knowledge_graph), [ontology](/Ontology_(information_science)) and encyclopedic [dictionary](/Dictionary) that was developed at the [NLP](/Natural_Language_Processing) group of the [Sapienza University of Rome](/Sapienza_University_of_Rome) under the supervision of [Roberto Navigli](/Roberto_Navigli). &#91;1&#93; &#91;2&#93; It was automatically created by linking [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) to the most popular computational [lexicon](/Dictionary) of the [English language](/English_language), [WordNet](/WordNet). The integration was performed using an automatic mapping and by filling in lexical gaps in resource‑poor [languages](/Language) through the use of [statistical machine translation](/Statistical_machine_translation). The result is an [encyclopedic dictionary](/Encyclopedic_dictionary) that provides [concepts](/Concept) and [named entities](/Named_entity) [lexicalized](/Lexicalization) in many languages and interconnects them with a large number of [semantic relations](/Semantic_relation). Additional lexicalizations and definitions are contributed by linking to freely licensed wordnets, [OmegaWiki](/OmegaWiki), the English [Wiktionary](/Wiktionary), [Wikidata](/Wikidata), [FrameNet](/FrameNet), [VerbNet](/VerbNet) and other resources. In analogy to [WordNet](/WordNet), BabelNet groups [words](/Word) in different languages into sets of [synonyms](/Synonyms) called [Babel synsets](/Synsets). For each [Babel synset](/Synsets) the system supplies short [glosses](/Definition) in numerous languages that are harvested from both [WordNet](/WordNet) and [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia).  

---  

## Statistics of BabelNet  

As of December&#160;2023 &#91;update&#93; , BabelNet (version 5.3) covers 600 [languages](/Language). It contains almost 23 million [synsets](/Synsets) and around 1.7 billion [word senses](/Word_sense) (regardless of their language). Each [Babel synset](/Synsets) contains, on average, two synonyms per language, i.e., two [word senses](/Word_sense). The semantic network includes all lexico‑semantic relations from [WordNet](/WordNet) ([hypernymy and hyponymy](/Hyponymy), [meronymy](/Meronymy) and [holonymy](/Holonymy), [antonymy](/Antonymy) and [synonymy](/Synonymy), etc.), amounting to roughly 364 000 relation edges, as well as an underspecified relatedness relation extracted from [Wikipedia](/Wikipedia) (approximately 1.9 billion edges). &#91;1&#93; Version 5.3 also links around 61 million images to [Babel synsets](/Synsets) and provides a [Lemon](/Lemon) [RDF](/Resource_Description_Framework) encoding of the resource, &#91;3&#93; which is accessible through a [SPARQL endpoint](/SPARQL_endpoint). Additionally, 2.67 million [synsets](/Synsets) are assigned [domain labels](/Domain_label).  

---  

## Applications  

BabelNet has been demonstrated to empower a variety of multilingual [natural language processing](/Natural_language_processing) tasks. Its richly lexicalized [knowledge](/Knowledge) yields state‑of‑the‑art performance in several areas, including:  

* [Semantic relatedness](/Semantic_relatedness), &#91;4&#93; &#91;5&#93;  
* Multilingual [word‑sense disambiguation](/Word-sense_disambiguation) and [entity linking](/Entity_linking), most notably through the [Babelfy](/Babelfy) system, &#91;7&#93;  
* [Game with a purpose](/Game_with_a_purpose) initiatives that harness player interaction for linguistic annotation, &#91;8&#93;  

---  

## Prizes and acknowledgments  

The resource has received several distinctions, among them the META prize 2015 for “groundbreaking work in overcoming language barriers through a multilingual lexicalised semantic network and ontology making use of heterogeneous data sources”. The Artificial Intelligence Journal article that introduced BabelNet &#91;1&#93; was awarded the Prominent Paper Award in 2017. &#91;9&#93; Moreover, BabelNet was highlighted in a [Time](/Time_(magazine)) magazine feature &#91;10&#93; that discussed innovative lexical knowledge resources on the Web.  

